1 the items listed in 45-9-107 with intent to manufacture methamphetamine; or
2 (c) causes or permits a child to inhale, be exposed to, have contact with, or ingest
3 methamphetamine or be exposed to or have contact with methamphetamine paraphernaliaa dangerous drug
4 listed in Schedules I through V as provided in Title 50, chapter 32, part 2, unless under the direction of a
5 physician or licensed medical provider.
6 (4) A parent, guardian, or other person supervising the welfare of a child less than 16 years of age
7 may verbally or in writing request a person who is 18 years of age or older and who has no legal right of
8 supervision or control over the child to stop contacting the child if the requester believes that the contact is not
9 in the child's best interests. If the person continues to contact the child, the parent, guardian, or other person
10 supervising the welfare of the child may petition or the county attorney may upon the person's request petition
11 for an order of protection under Title 40, chapter 15. To the extent that they are consistent with this subsection,
12 the provisions of Title 40, chapter 15, apply. A person who purposely or knowingly violates an order of
13 protection commits the offense of endangering the welfare of children and upon conviction shall be sentenced
14 as provided in subsection (5)(a).
15 (5) (a) Except as provided in subsection (5)(b), a person convicted of endangering the welfare of
16 children shall be fined an amount not to exceed $500 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any term not to
17 exceed 6 months, or both. A person convicted of a second offense of endangering the welfare of children shall
18 be fined an amount not to exceed $1,000 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any term not to exceed 6
19 months, or both.
20 (b) A person convicted under subsection (3) is guilty of a felony and shall be imprisoned in the
21 state prison for a term not to exceed 5 years and may be fined an amount not to exceed $10,000, or both. If a
22 child suffers serious bodily injury, the offender shall be fined an amount not to exceed $25,000 or be imprisoned
23 for a term not to exceed 10 years, or both. Prosecution or conviction of a violation of subsection (3) does not
24 bar prosecution or conviction for any other crime committed by the offender as part of the same conduct.
25 (6) On the issue of whether there has been a violation of the duty of care, protection, and support,
26 the following, in addition to all other admissible evidence, is admissible: cruel treatment; abuse; infliction of
27 unnecessary and cruel punishment; abandonment; neglect; lack of proper medical care, clothing, shelter, and
28 food; and evidence of past bodily injury.
